<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="107" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Found at the edges of Tonle Sap River and Lake, ponds and in paddy fields at Kampong Chhnang, Banteay Meanchey, and Siem Reap Provinces (locality no. 3, 4, 8, 11, 16, 40, 42, 43, and 44).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="107" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="107">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Morelet" baseAuthorityYear="1866" class="Gastropoda" family="Bithyniidae" genus="Bithynia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bithynia siamensis subsp. goniomphalus" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subSpecies" species="siamensis" subSpecies="goniomphalus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Bithynia siamensis goniomphalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is of medical importance because it is an intermediate host of the zoonotic parasite, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Poirier" baseAuthorityYear="1886" class="Trematoda" family="Opisthorchiidae" genus="Opisthorchis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Opisthorchis viverrini" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="viverrini">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Opisthorchis viverrini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Poirier, 1886) (TROPMED Medical Group 1986). The role of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Morelet" baseAuthorityYear="1866" class="Gastropoda" family="Bithyniidae" genus="Bithynia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bithynia siamensis subsp. goniomphalus" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subSpecies" species="siamensis" subSpecies="goniomphalus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="107">Bithynia siamensis goniomphalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the transmission of this parasite in Cambodia has not been investigated in detail, although the parasite has been recorded in freshwater fishes at the border of the Kandal-Takeo Provinces in the south (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.actatropica.2009.03.002" author="Touch, S" journalOrPublisher="Acta Tropica" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" pagination="108 - 113" refId="B89" refString="Touch, S, Komalamisra, C, Radomyos, P, Waikagul, J, 2009. Discovery of Opisthorchis viverrini metacercariae in freshwater fish in southern Cambodia. Acta Tropica 111: 108 - 113, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.actatropica.2009.03.002" title="Discovery of Opisthorchis viverrini metacercariae in freshwater fish in southern Cambodia." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.actatropica.2009.03.002" volume="111" year="2009">Touch et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
), and cases of human infections are well-studied throughout the country (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.parint.2011.08.014" author="Sithithaworn, P" journalOrPublisher="Parasitology International" pageId="0" pageNumber="107" pagination="10 - 16" refId="B86" refString="Sithithaworn, P, Andrews, RH, Van De, N, Wongsaroj, T, Sinuon, M, Odermatt, P, Nawa, Y, Liang, S, Brindley, PJ, Sripa, B, 2012. The current status of opisthorchiasis and clonorchiasis in the Mekong basin. Parasitology International 61: 10 - 16, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.parint.2011.08.014" title="The current status of opisthorchiasis and clonorchiasis in the Mekong basin." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.parint.2011.08.014" volume="61" year="2012">Sithithaworn et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
